    title="CC26xx RF core — dual-CPU architecture"
    tag="Highest-ROI differentiator"
    why="<b>Where this bites you:</b> most candidates won't know this. Knowing why some wireless MCUs include a <i>second CPU</i> for radio work — and what it implies for your application code — signals you understand the silicon split. Step through one radio command."
    takeaway="<b>Why it matters (say all four):</b> ① RF timing is deterministic — your app bugs can't break a connection event. ② RF certification is handled at silicon-vendor level — you never touch RF firmware. ③ The M4 can <b>sleep through connection events</b> — huge for power. ④ Rule: never call RF APIs from arbitrary ISRs — use RF driver callbacks. On newer secure MCUs, the same split may be reinforced with TrustZone boundaries."
